(154, 3, 'During an Earthquake', 'Drop, cover and hold. Move only as far as necessary to reach a safe place.\nIf indoors, stay there. It is safer to stay indoors until the shaking stops than it is safe to exit. When going outdoors, move quickly away from the building to prevent injury from falling debris.\nIf outdoors, find a spot away from buildings, trees, streetlights and power lines and over passes. Drop to the ground and stay there until the shaking stops.\nIf in a vehicle, pull over at a clear location and stop. Stay in the vehicle with seatbelt fastened until the shaking stops.\nIf in a high rise building, expect the fire alarms and sprinkler systems to go off during an earthquake. Check for and extinguish small fires. DO NOT use elevators.\nIf in a coastal area, move to higher ground. Earthquakes often generate tsunamis.\nIf in a mountainous area or near unstable slopes or cliffs, be alert for falling rock and other debris that could be loosened by the eathquake. Also, watch for landslides that could be triggered by the earthquake.', 1, '2011-10-12 16:37:24', 1),
